To get a full folder structure diagram in Markdown (.md) format directly from VS Code on Linux, you have two primary options: using a built-in terminal command or installing a specialized extension.
Option 1: Using the Linux Terminal (No Install Required)
You can use the native Linux tree command within the VS Code integrated terminal (Ctrl + `).
This is the fastest way to "spit out" a structure you can copy and paste. 
Open the Terminal in VS Code.
Run the following command to generate a clean ASCII tree:
bash
tree -a -I '.git|node_modules'

-a: Includes hidden files.
-I '.git|node_modules': Ignores folders you usually don't want in a diagram.
To save it directly to a file, use the redirection operator:
bash
tree -a -I '.git|node_modules' > structure.md

Format as Markdown: Open the new file and wrap the text in triple backticks (```) so it renders as a code block in your .md viewer. 
Option 2: Using a VS Code Extension (Visual & Automated)
If you want a one-click solution that automatically formats the output into Markdown, 
you can install an extension from the Marketplace. 
Draw Folder Structure:
Usage: Right-click any folder in the Explorer sidebar and select "Generate Markdown structure".
Result: It automatically copies a formatted tree to your clipboard and often opens it in a new tab for you to save.
VSCode Folder Structure Generator:
Usage: Open the Command Palette (Ctrl + Shift + P) and type "Generate Folder Structure". 
Option 3: Diagrams as Code (Mermaid)
If you want a more "graphical" diagram that lives inside your Markdown, use Mermaid.js syntax. VS Code has built-in support for rendering these previews. 
markdown
```mermaid
graph TD
    Root[Project Root] --> Src[src]
    Root --> Docs[docs]
    Src --> Auth[auth.py]
    Src --> Main[main.py]
